lized": true, "mention": "GnRH receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9956865906715393, "span": {"begin": 561, "end": 575}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "pituitary gonadotroph cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.8968817591667175, "span": {"begin": 594, "end": 621}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:59352"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "gonadotropin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.985104501247406, "span": {"begin": 634, "end": 646}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:9567"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "G-protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9953611493110657, "span": {"begin": 661, "end": 670}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:23236"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "phospholipase C", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9955713152885437, "span": {"begin": 672, "end": 687}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "mitogen-activated protein kinase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9958346486091614, "span": {"begin": 704, "end": 736}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5595"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MAPK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9939537048339844, "span": {"begin": 738, "end": 742}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2796"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GnRH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9896222352981567, "span": {"begin": 775, "end": 779}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 801, "end": 803}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2796"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GnRH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9908247590065002, "span": {"begin": 825, "end": 829}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6046"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "FSH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9969661831855774, "span": {"begin": 851, "end": 854}}], "text": "Increased Gonadotropin-Releasing Hormone (GnRH) and resulting increased gonadotropins, with focus on Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and Luteinizing hormone (LH), have been studied in laboratory mammals by addition of estrogen compounds (Clarkson et al. 2008), toxicants (Wang et al. 2014), and modifying diet (Bo et al. 2022). &nbsp;Gene-knock out studies have been useful in showing the essentiality of GnRH in reproductive development and puberty, with GnRH-null animals failing to increase gonadotropin levels (Clarkson et al. 2008). &nbsp;GnRH binds to GnRH receptors on the surface of pituitary gonadotroph cells, triggering gonadotropin production by G-protein, phospholipase C activation, and mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK) pathway activation. &nbsp;Fast GnRH pulse secretion cues LH production, and slow GnRH pulse secretion cues FSH production.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:21:03 +0000 2026"}